  "formatedtext": "Dalmatius of Constantinople -  Dalmatius of Constantinople  Saint Dalmatius (died AD 440) was archimandrite of the Dalmatian Monastery in Constantinople . He also held the title Archimandrite of the Monasteries , making him the city's chief monk. [1] Dalmatius served in the second company of Guards under Theodosius the Great . He was married with a family. Experiencing a call to monastic life, he received instruction from Isaac of Dalmatia . [2] Like most of the city's monks, he was an opponent of the Nestorian heresy , and he played an important role in the downfall of Nestorius . Following Cyril of Alexandria 's instructions, Dalmatius led an army of monks to the palace of Theodosius II , and shouted abuse against him, because he had sided with the Nestorians and annulled the First Council of Ephesus . [3] Because this was the first time Dalmatius had left his monastery in 48 years, the emperor was astonished to see the holy man abroad and granted his request to hear Cyril's case, which led ultimately to Cyril's vindication. [4] The feast day of St Dalmatius is August 3. References [ edit ] ^ Daniel Caner, Wandering, Begging Monks:Spiritual Authority and the Promotion of Monasticism in Late Antiquity , (Berkeley: University of California Press, 2002), 212-23. ^ \"Dalmatius\" . BiblicalCyclopedia . Retrieved June 25, 2020 . ^ Edward Gibbon , Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire , 47 ^ Caner, 219-20. External links [ edit ] St. Dalmatius Ss. Isaac, Dalmatius, and Faustus Portals Access related topics Saints portal Biography portal Catholicism portal Turkey portal Authority control GND : 102389772 VIAF : 20069112 WorldCat Identities (via VIAF): 20069112 Retrieved from \" https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Dalmatius_of_Constantinople&oldid=964504707 \" Categories : 5th-century Christian saints Saints from Constantinople 440 deaths Saints from Roman Anatolia 5th-century Byzantine people Hidden categories:  articles with GND identifiers  artic